00:47:55.720 --> 00:47:56.020
Yeah.

00:47:56.020 --> 00:47:58.420
Oh, that's a really interesting way to leverage the community.

00:47:58.420 --> 00:48:01.700
Not just the core programming skills, but the other stuff as well.

00:48:01.700 --> 00:48:02.040
Yeah.

00:48:02.040 --> 00:48:15.360
And I think it's really essential that we have this kind of approach because I think the thing that's difficult about running a community of volunteers is that if you run a business, well, I can like buy productivity.

00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:17.760
I pay you, you make me something, right?

00:48:17.760 --> 00:48:20.960
But when I have a community of volunteers, I can't pay you.

00:48:20.960 --> 00:48:22.220
I don't have any money to pay you with.

00:48:22.220 --> 00:48:25.380
So the only way I can get you to do something is to motivate you.

00:48:25.380 --> 00:48:32.480
And there's some intrinsic motivation in being part of something good and wholesome like this.

00:48:32.480 --> 00:48:38.320
I think the culture helps bring people in and like from an altruistic point of view, like they just want to help out.

00:48:38.320 --> 00:48:40.700
They want to be a good force in the universe.

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:55.800
But ultimately, if you really want strong, directed initiative and motivation, I think you have to find like a synergy, a sort of a thing where your personal goals align with the goals of the community, right?

00:48:55.800 --> 00:49:00.440
So you want to do something for us that's good for you, but it's also good for us.

00:49:00.440 --> 00:49:02.660
That's the perfect way to motivate people.

00:49:02.660 --> 00:49:10.220
So by providing as many ways as possible for people to get involved like that, it means that people can come in and actually like build their skill set.

00:49:10.580 --> 00:49:13.620
